[14:15:08] {"event": "tool_result", "tool": "view", "is_error": false, "result": {"status": "success", "file": "/Users/virginia.zambudio/PlaywrightAutomation/context-pack/system/execution-protocol.md", "content": "81:   - §12.4 Verify before use (subagent output is input, not ground truth)\n82: - §13 — Code-location discipline (consult `codebase-map.md` before any discovery scan; code-searching skills only)\n83:   - §13.1 The rule — consult before scan, not never scan\n84:   - §13.2 When the map is insufficient — flag the gap\n85:   - §13.3 Applies to (code-searching skills only)\n86:   - §13.4 Composition with §12\n87:   - §12.5 Fallback (no subagent capability → inline exploration)\n88:   - §12.6 Skill-level enforcement\n89: - §14 — Parallel fan-out (write-capable subagent fan-out over independent units; harness-agnostic, optional)\n90:   - §14.1 When to fan out (and when not)\n91:   - §14.2 Worker contract (incl. §14.2.1 sharded progress)\n92:   - §14.3 Coordinator contract (shard → dispatch → merge → sidecar last)\n93:   - §14.4 Verify before use\n94:   - §14.5 Fallback (no delegation capability → inline unit loop)\n95:   - §14.6 Skill-level enforcement\n96: \n97: ---\n98: \n99: \n100: ## Section files\n101: \n102: Non-universal sections now live as individual files under `execution-protocol/`.\n103: Read only those your route selects (see the routing rule above); each is readable\n104: standalone with its original § numbering intact. The **universal** sections (§2,\n105: §10.5, §11 — required by every skill) remain inlined below.\n106: \n107: | § | Location |\n108: |---|----------|\n109: | §1  Session Identity | `execution-protocol/01-session-identity.md` |\n110: | §2  `_progress.json` | inline below (universal) |\n111: | §3  IMPL-STATE | `execution-protocol/03-impl-state.md` |\n112: | §4  Memory Bank | `execution-protocol/04-memory-bank.md` |\n113: | §5  FIC recovery | `execution-protocol/05-fic-recovery.md` |\n114: | §6  Dual-format | `execution-protocol/06-dual-format.md` |\n115: | §7  REPAIR / §7.3 REBUILD | `execution-protocol/07-repair-mode.md` |\n116: | §8  Deviations | `execution-protocol/08-deviations.md` |\n117: | §9  Non-interactive | `execution-protocol/09-non-interactive.md` |\n118: | §10 Section generation | `execution-protocol/10-section-generation.md` |\n119: | §10.5 Tool discipline | inline below (universal) |\n120: | §11 Output sidecar | inline below (universal) |\n121: | §12 Delegated exploration | `execution-protocol/12-delegated-exploration.md` |\n122: | §13 Code-location | `execution-protocol/13-code-location.md` |\n123: | §14 Parallel fan-out | `execution-protocol/14-parallel-fanout.md` |\n124: \n125: A skill's route (e.g. `§2 → §10 → §10.5 → §11`) resolves each §N via this table:\n126: universal sections are already here; the rest are one file-read away. Existing\n127: \"see execution-protocol.md §N\" citations in the 123 skills keep working through\n128: this one redirect hop — no skill edits required.\n129: \n130: ---\n131: \n132: ## 2. _progress.json — Early Signal Write\n133: \n134: **Purpose:** Prevents the orchestrator coordinator from sending SIGINT to a running skill.\n135: \n136: Write this as the **FIRST file action** in any skill execution (before creating any other outputs):\n137: \n138: ```json\n139: {\n140:   \"skill\": \"{skill-name}\",\n141:   \"session_id\": \"{SESSION_ID}\",\n142:   \"status\": \"RUNNING\",\n143:   \"started_at\": \"{ISO timestamp}\",\n144:   \"completed_at\": null,\n145:   \"total\": 0,\n146:   \"completed\": 0,\n147:   \"items\": []\n148: }\n149: ```\n150: \n151: Write to: `{output_folder}/_progress.json`\n152: \n153: **Update cadence:**\n154: - On FIC trigger (Section 5): `\"status\": \"COMPACTION_NEEDED\"`\n155: - On completion: `\"status\": \"COMPLETED\"`, `\"completed_at\": \"{ISO timestamp}\"`\n156: - On failure: `\"status\": \"FAILED\"`, `\"completed_at\": \"{ISO timestamp}\"`\n157: \n158: **Schema variants.** A skill picks ONE shape based on its work model. The common\n159: envelope (`skill`, `session_id`, `status`, `started_at`, `completed_at`) is identical\n160: across variants.\n161: \n162: - **List shape (default — shown above)** — uses `total`, `completed`, `items[]`. Suits\n163:   skills that produce many discrete artifacts (e.g. `implementing-code` writing source\n164:   files; `planning-code-tasks` tracking task entries).\n165: - **Section shape** — uses `skeleton_written` (bool) + `sections{}` map. Suits skills\n166:   that produce a single multi-section spec file from large unstructured inputs. See\n167:   **Section 10** for the full protocol (skeleton-first + one-section-per-write +\n168:   source extraction + CONTINUE re-entry).\n169: \n170: ### Skill-Level Enforcement (FIRST ACTION / LAST ACTION)\n171: \n172: Every skill MUST include these two inline callouts — agents do not reliably follow\n173: protocol-only references for session bookend writes:\n174: \n175: **At session start** (after folder creation, before any other file write):\n176: \n177: > **FIRST ACTION — MANDATORY:** Write `_progress.json` to the output folder before any other file write.\n178: > This prevents the orchestrator from sending SIGINT.\n179: \n180: Include the minimal JSON schema inline in the skill so the agent can write immediately\n181: without reading this file first. Use `\"session_id\": \"initializing\"` as placeholder.\n182: \n183: **At session end** (after all spec files written, after Memory Bank writes):\n184: \n185: > **LAST ACTION — MANDATORY:** Update `_progress.json` status to `COMPLETED` with `completed_at` timestamp.\n186: > If the session failed, set status to `FAILED` instead.\n187: \n188: These callouts are NOT infrastructure duplication — they are the minimum viable bridge\n189: between protocol and agent behavior. The full lifecycle lives here; the callouts trigger it.\n190: \n191: **For `implementing-code` only** — also include `output_contract` (survives compaction):\n192: \n193: ```json\n194: {\n195:   \"skill\": \"implementing-code\",\n196:   \"session_id\": \"{SESSION_ID}\",\n197:   \"status\": \"RUNNING\",\n198:   \"output_contract\": {\n199:     \"progress_folder_path\": \"{progress_folder_path}\",\n200:     \"impl_state_file\": \"IMPL-STATE-{session_id}.md\","}}
[14:15:26] {"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "\nThe routing rule for `framework-exploration` skill:\n- It's a section-shape skill → §2 → §10 → §10.5 → §11\n- No §1 (not in code-development family)\n- No §12, §13, §14\n\nMy priority tasks:\n1. Write _progress.json FIRST (before anything else)\n2. Check existing framework paths to determine scenario\n3. Load the framework-exploration skill\n4. Execute accordingly\n\nThe additional instructions (human guidance payload) says to fix specific test failures:\n1. TC-83232 newsletter footer - locator `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` times out\n2. TC-83240 login page - locator `input[name=\"email\"][type=\"email\"]` times out on `/myaccount`\n3. TC-83238 in-store pickup - locator `p.cursor-pointer.text-primary` with \"set your store\" text times out (Firefox + WebKit)\n\nThese are FLAKY TEST FIXES, not framework architecture work. The \"Additional Instructions\" section says \"Fix this issues\" - this is runtime human guidance that overrides the framework-exploration task scope.\n\nWait - re-reading: The task prompt says \"framework-exploration\" skill, but the \"Additional Instructions\" (which is playlist global context from the Stepwise workflow) says to fix these specific test failures. These instructions come as \"Playlist global context\" under \"Additional Instructions\" in the Run metadata.\n\nThe human guidance file is empty (no messages returned). The \"Additional Instructions\" are embedded in the prompt itself as the playlist global context.\n\nSo my actual task is:\n- Run the framework-exploration skill BUT the \"Additional Instructions\" clarify the real goal is to fix these flaky test failures.\n\nActually, looking more carefully: The system is running a Stepwise workflow called `quality-engineering-web-automation`. The \"Additional Instructions\" section says the playlist global context is \"Fix this issues [list of test failures]\". This means the overall workflow goal is to fix these test failures.\n\nHowever, the CURRENT STEP is `framework-exploration`. The skill I need to run is `framework-exploration` which analyzes the existing framework. But given that the actual bugs are known test failures, I should focus on fixing those specific failures rather than running a full framework exploration.\n\nActually, re-reading the agent behavior rules: \"Playlist global context: Fix this issues...\" - This is the overall context for what the playlist (multi-step workflow) is trying to achieve. The current step is framework-exploration.\n\nBut given the context - the framework already exists (this is Scenario 2/3), and the failures are clearly selector/timing issues - I should:\n1. Write _progress.json\n2. Check if FRAMEWORK-SPEC already exists (Scenario 3)\n3. If not, do quick framework exploration focused on the failing tests\n4. Fix the actual test failures (since that's the playlist goal and human context)\n\nLet me check what exists first, then proceed.\n"}}
