s.env.CI ? 0 : 800,\n37:       args: [\n38:         '--lang=en-CA',\n39:         '--disable-features=Translate,TranslateUI',\n40:         '--disable-translate',\n41:         '--no-default-browser-check',\n42:       ],\n43:     },\n44:     extraHTTPHeaders: {\n45:       'Accept-Language': 'en-CA,en;q=0.9',\n46:     },\n47:     /* Trace disabled to avoid ZIP stream corruption bug in Playwright 1.61 */\n48:     trace: 'off',\n49:     /* Screenshots are handled by the custom afterEach in helpers/evidence.ts\n50:        (saved to artifacts/outputs/ with TC number + timestamp in the filename) */\n51:     screenshot: 'off',\n52:   },\n53: \n54:   /* Configure projects for major browsers */\n55:   projects: [\n56:     {\n57:       name: 'chromium',\n58:       use: { ...devices['Desktop Chrome'] },\n59:     },\n60: \n61:     {\n62:       name: 'firefox',\n63:       use: { ...devices['Desktop Firefox'] },\n64:     },\n65: \n66:     {\n67:       name: 'webkit',\n68:       use: { ...devices['Desktop Safari'] },\n69:     },\n70: \n71:     /* Microsoft Edge -- AD-09: 4th browser project added 2026-07-14.\n72:        Uses msedge channel; requires separate install step in CI:\n73:          npx playwright install msedge\n74:        (NOT included in --with-deps on ubuntu-latest) */\n75:     {\n76:       name: 'edge',\n77:       use: { ...devices['Desktop Chrome'], channel: 'msedge' },\n78:     },\n79:   ],\n80: });"}}
[14:17:16] {"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "\nKey observation: `playwright.config.ts` has `geolocation: { latitude: 49.2827, longitude: -123.1207 }` and `permissions: ['geolocation']` - this is Vancouver, BC coordinates. This means ALL browsers (including Firefox and WebKit) will have geolocation set to Vancouver. This means the site MIGHT auto-detect a store, making \"Set your store\" link not visible (replaced by \"Check availability at other stores\").\n\nBut the `openStoreSelectorDialog()` in ProductDetailPage.ts already handles this with a fallback. So why does it still fail on Firefox/WebKit?\n\nWait - the error says the OLD code failed (timeout 15_000ms on `setYourStoreLink`). The current code has been updated with a try/catch and 5_000 timeout, then falls back to `checkAvailabilityLink`. So the current code should handle this case better.\n\nThe error trace shown in the \"Additional Instructions\" is from the PREVIOUS test run. The files (pages/LoginPage.ts, pages/ProductDetailPage.ts, tests/home-page.spec.ts, tests/pdp.spec.ts) are all modified (M) from the git status. This means the fixes were applied but NOT yet re-tested.\n\nMy job is to:\n1. Verify the current fixes look correct\n2. Make any additional improvements if needed\n3. Complete the framework exploration task\n\nLet me look more carefully at remaining potential issues:\n\n**TC-83238 (Firefox/WebKit) - current openStoreSelectorDialog():**\n- Scrolls inStorePickupRadio into view\n- Waits 2.5s\n- Tries `setYourStoreLink` with 5_000 timeout, catches failure\n- If that fails, tries `checkAvailabilityLink` with 15_000 timeout\n\nPotential issue: What if NEITHER link is visible? What if the page shows \"Check in-store availability\" or some other text? The geolocation-based store pre-selection might show a completely different UI. The fallback uses `.filter({ hasText: /check availability at other stores/i })` which is specific text.\n\n**TC-83232 (Chromium/Edge) - newsletter:**\nThe selector `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` might be correct but the element might be hidden via visibility:hidden or display:none even after scrolling. The Builder.io content might require a different trigger.\n\nOne thing I notice: the current spec at line 413 step says \"Scroll to footer newsletter form\" but looking at the test file body, this step contains:\n- page.evaluate scroll to bottom\n- waitForLoadState networkidle 30s\n- waitForTimeout 1s\n- scroll to bottom again\n- waitForTimeout 500ms\n- scrollIntoViewIfNeeded\n- retry loop 15 iterations\n- waitFor 45_000\n\nThat's actually quite robust. The question is whether the SELECTOR is right.\n\nActually, wait - looking at the error trace again carefully:\n```\n> 414 |             await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });\n```\n\nBut looking at the current test file at line 452:\n```\nawait homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 45_000 });\n```\n\nThese line numbers don't match. The error was from an OLDER version of the test file. So the current code is already updated with improved retry logic. The modifications shown in git status confirm this.\n\nMy conclusion: The error report in \"Additional Instructions\" was captured from a previous test run. The current code (as shown by the (M) modified status) has already been updated to address these issues. \n\nHowever, there are a few things I should still verify and potentially improve:\n\n1. **TC-83240 Login** - The error says `waiting for locator('input[name=\"email\"][type=\"email\"]').first()`. Current LoginPage.ts navigates to `/auth/login` instead of `/myaccount`. But what if `/auth/login` itself renders differently? The emailInput locator `input[name=\"email\"][type=\"email\"]` should work on the login form. The 45s timeout should be sufficient.\n\n2. **TC-83232 Newsletter** - The selector `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` - is this robust enough? Let me use the browser to check the current state.\n\n3. **TC-83238 In-Store Pickup** - The fallback logic looks sound.\n\nI think the best approach is:\n1. Use the browser to verify the newsletter selector on the actual site\n2. Check if the login page at /auth/login has the expected form\n3. Make any remaining selector fixes\n4. Then write the framework spec\n\nActually, given that this is a framework-exploration skill task with a \"fix these issues\" directive, I should:\n1. Do a quick browser inspection of the failing selectors\n2. Fix any remaining issues\n3. Write the FRAMEWORK-SPEC and FRAMEWORK-AUDIT\n"}}
